 Political tensions impeded key structural reforms such as comprehensive reforms of state-owned enterprises, which are yet to take place, and hampered growth, another key credit challenge, said Moody s. The ratings agency released a statement on Wednesday afternoon. Moody&#8217;s currently rates South Africa two notches above junk status with a negative outlook. This comes in the wake of S&amp;P commenting on the politics affecting the state, particularly within the ANC, which is experiencing a succession battle between outgoing AU chairperson Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma and Deputy President Cyril Ramaphosa. For more news your way, follow The Citizen on Facebook and Twitter.